{"id":"mai-tlv9","kind":"ticket","type":"task","title":"ADR: mai as substrate, domain tools as separate binaries","priority":1,"tags":["adr","architecture","hooman"],"body":"## Context\n\nFrom conversation about adding changelog support (replacing tinychange), we hit the architectural question: should mai keep growing commands (pr, docs, changelog) or should those be separate tools consuming mai's substrate?\n\n### The conversation\n\nHooman:\n\u003e I'm starting to feel we're doing the unix philosophy wrong though—\n\u003e so— mai domain is substrate. PR, docs, changelog are actually separate apps using mai?\n\u003e what's the ideal shape for this— so mai remains a clear boundary / interface\n\n### Current state\n\n`pkg/notes` Engine interface is already clean — 19 methods, knows nothing about tickets/PRs/docs. But domain logic leaks:\n\n- `cmd/mai/pr.go` (480 lines) — PR workflow baked into mai binary\n- `pkg/notes/docs.go` (693 lines) — CRDT doc sync inside the substrate package (!)\n- `cmd/mai/daemon.go` (343 lines) — docs watcher daemon inside mai\n- `cmd/mai/lattice.go` (291 lines) — docs lattice rendering inside mai\n\nTotal: ~1800 lines of domain logic that doesn't operate on the note primitive generically.\n\n## Decision\n\n**mai is the substrate. Domain workflows are separate binaries.**\n\n### What stays in mai (the substrate)\n\nOperations on the note primitive, generically:\n\n```\ncreate / append / get / fold      — CRUD on notes\nfind / list / context / refs      — query\nsync / hooks / guard              — plumbing\nbranch use / merge                — scoping\ndoctor / rebuild / kinds          — diagnostics\n--json everywhere                 — machine interface\n```\n\nPlus zero-logic shortcuts: `mai ticket`, `mai warn`, `mai adr`, `mai artifact`, `mai review` — these are one-line wrappers around `mai create -k X`. No domain logic. They stay.\n\n### What becomes separate binaries\n\n| Binary | Domain | Current location | Moves to |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `mai-pr` | PR workflow (create from branch, diff, accept/reject, merge) | `cmd/mai/pr.go` | `cmd/mai-pr/` |\n| `mai-docs` | CRDT doc sync, Obsidian compat, daemon | `pkg/notes/docs.go` + `cmd/mai/daemon.go` + `cmd/mai/lattice.go` | `cmd/mai-docs/` + `pkg/docs/` |\n| `mai-changelog` | Replaces tinychange, aggregates artifacts | not yet written | `cmd/mai-changelog/` |\n\n### The boundary test\n\n\u003e Does it operate on the note primitive generically? → stays in mai.\n\u003e Does it understand a specific domain (PRs have branches, docs have CRDT, changelogs have versions)? → separate tool.\n\n### Discovery pattern\n\nGit-style subcommand discovery: `mai pr` looks for `mai-pr` on PATH. This gives:\n\n1. mai stays small and stable\n2. Third parties can build `mai-whatever`\n3. Each tool has its own release cycle\n4. `go install github.com/cygnusfear/maitake/cmd/mai-pr@latest` works\n\n### The Engine interface as API contract\n\n`pkg/notes.Engine` (19 methods) is the programmatic API. Separate binaries can either:\n- Import `pkg/notes` directly (same Go module, zero overhead)\n- Shell out to `mai --json` (language-agnostic, works for non-Go tools like ramboard)\n\n### Migration path\n\n1. Extract `pkg/notes/docs.go` → `pkg/docs/` (fixes the layer violation)\n2. Move `cmd/mai/pr.go` → `cmd/mai-pr/main.go`\n3. Move daemon/lattice → `cmd/mai-docs/`\n4. Add subcommand discovery to mai: if `mai foo` isn't built-in, exec `mai-foo`\n5. Build `mai-changelog` as the first \"born outside\" tool\n6. `go install` installs all binaries from the same module\n\n### What doesn't change\n\n- `pkg/notes` Engine interface — untouched\n- `mai ticket`, `mai warn`, `mai adr` shortcuts — stay as-is\n- Skills that teach agents — they still say `mai pr`, it just dispatches to `mai-pr`\n- User-facing CLI — `mai pr show` still works, just dispatches differently\n\n## Consequences\n\n- (+) mai stays under 500 lines of real logic\n- (+) Clean boundary — Engine interface is the contract\n- (+) Third-party extensibility via PATH discovery\n- (+) Each domain tool can iterate independently\n- (+) `pkg/notes/docs.go` stops violating the layer rule\n- (-) Multiple binaries to install (mitigated: same Go module, one `go install`)\n- (-) Subcommand discovery adds ~20 lines to main.go\n\n## Goal\nEstablish mai as a clean substrate with domain tools as separate binaries, starting with mai-changelog as proof of the pattern\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] mai binary contains only substrate operations (create/append/find/fold/sync/hooks) + zero-logic shortcuts\n- [ ] mai-pr is a separate binary, discoverable via `mai pr`\n- [ ] mai-docs is a separate binary with CRDT/daemon/lattice logic extracted from pkg/notes\n- [ ] mai-changelog exists as first born-outside tool, replacing tinychange\n- [ ] pkg/notes/docs.go is extracted to pkg/docs/ (layer violation fixed)\n- [ ] Subcommand discovery: `mai X` tries `mai-X` on PATH if X isn't built-in\n- [ ] All binaries installable from same Go module\n\n## Verification\n- [ ] mai --help shows only substrate commands + shortcuts\n- [ ] mai pr still works (dispatches to mai-pr)\n- [ ] mai-changelog new / merge works as tinychange replacement\n- [ ] go install ./cmd/... installs all binaries\n- [ ] pkg/notes has zero imports of domain-specific packages","timestamp":"2026-04-04T11:54:33Z","branch":"main"}
